        <h2>The Fundamental Shift: From Ranking to Citation</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The search paradigm that defined digital marketing for two decades — optimise to rank, rank to be found — is being replaced by a different model: optimise to be cited, be cited to be known.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          This is not a gradual evolution. It is a categorical change in how information reaches people. When a user types a query into Google in 2026, a substantial proportion of the results page is now occupied by an AI-generated answer that synthesises information from multiple sources before the user has read a single blue link. When they ask ChatGPT, Perplexity, or Microsoft Copilot a research question, there is no results page at all — only an answer, with one to three sources named.
        </p>

        <p>
          The implications for search marketing are profound. A brand that ranks third on page one of Google for a competitive query may still be invisible in the AI-generated answer that appears above those results. A brand with a modest backlink profile but exceptional entity clarity and content structure may be cited in every major AI platform for its target queries. Rank and citation are correlated, but they are not the same thing, and the gap between them is widening.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is the claim at the heart of AI optimization: getting cited by AI systems requires a distinct strategy — one that the traditional SEO playbook does not fully address. The discipline that addresses it is <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO)</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: What Actually Changed -->
