        <h2>What Actually Changed in Search</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Three technical developments, arriving in close succession, have permanently altered the mechanics of search visibility.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Retrieval-Augmented Generation at Scale</h3>
        <p>
          Modern AI search systems do not simply retrieve a list of documents ranked by relevance — they synthesise those documents into a single coherent response. This process, known as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), means the intermediary step of "user clicks link, user reads page" has been removed for a growing proportion of queries. The AI reads the pages and delivers the distilled answer. Your content is consumed — but the user may never visit your site.
        </p>

        <p>
          For brands, this changes the economics of content. The value is no longer only in clicks generated; it is also in the citation and attribution that shapes brand perception at the moment of answer delivery. Being named as the source in a synthesised response carries authority signals that accrue even without a page visit.
        </p>

        <h3>The Winner-Takes-Most Dynamic</h3>
        <p>
          Traditional search distributes attention across ten results on page one. AI search concentrates it in one to three cited sources. The competitive stakes are fundamentally different. In SEO, ranking fifth is suboptimal but not invisible. In AI search, if your brand is not among the cited sources, it does not exist for that query.
        </p>

        <p>
          This concentration effect is most pronounced on commercial and research queries — precisely the queries that drive business outcomes. When a buyer asks an AI assistant "which project management tools are best for remote agencies?", the tools named in the response have already won the consideration set. The others are not competing — they are absent.
        </p>

        <h3>Cross-Platform Fragmentation</h3>
        <p>
          A decade ago, "search" meant Google. Today, meaningful search activity occurs across Google AI Overviews, Perplexity, ChatGPT, Copilot, Gemini, and increasingly within voice interfaces and embedded AI assistants. Each platform uses different retrieval mechanisms, different training data, and different citation preferences. A brand can be prominently cited on Perplexity and effectively invisible on Google AI Overviews, or vice versa.
        </p>

        <p>
          This fragmentation creates a new requirement: cross-model visibility strategy. Understanding how to optimise for each platform — and which platforms matter most for your target audience — is a core competency of modern search marketing that did not exist five years ago.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: SEO Is Not Dead -->
