        <h2>SEO Is Not Dead — But It Is Insufficient</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The assertion that "SEO is dead" is wrong, and it is counterproductive — a strong SEO foundation is a prerequisite for AI search visibility, not an obstacle to it.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          AI retrieval systems do not operate in a vacuum. Google AI Overviews draw directly from pages that rank in Google's traditional index. Perplexity and ChatGPT use their own crawlers, but they weight authority signals that correlate heavily with SEO fundamentals: domain trust, backlink profiles, consistent topical depth, and technical crawlability. A site with poor SEO foundations will struggle in AI search, because AI systems will not retrieve pages they cannot efficiently crawl and process.
        </p>

        <p>
          What SEO does not address is the layer above retrieval: the selection and citation layer. Even if an AI system retrieves your page, it does not automatically cite your brand in the response. It selects the passages and sources that best serve the user's query, based on clarity, authority, and extractability. A page optimised purely for keyword density and backlinks may rank well in traditional search yet fail to be cited in AI-generated answers — because its content is not structured for extraction.
        </p>

        <p>
          The right mental model is one of stacked disciplines. SEO provides the technical and authority foundation. <a href="/geo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO builds on top of that foundation</a>, adding the content architecture, entity signals, and structured data that AI systems use to decide what to cite. Neither replaces the other. The brands that invest in both will outperform those invested in only one.
        </p>
