      <!-- Section 4: New Rules -->
      <section id="new-rules" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The New Rules of AI Visibility</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AI search systems cite content based on a different set of criteria than the signals that determine traditional organic rankings.</strong> Understanding these criteria is the foundation of effective AI optimization.
        </p>

        <h3>Rule 1: Entity Clarity Precedes Content Quality</h3>
        <p>
          Before an AI system can cite your brand, it must recognise your brand as a defined entity. Entity clarity means being consistently and accurately represented across the knowledge sources that large language models use as authority references: Wikipedia, Wikidata, Crunchbase, LinkedIn, industry directories, and major publications. A brand that exists only on its own website is effectively anonymous to AI models. Establishing entity presence across the knowledge ecosystem is the foundational step of AI optimization — and it is one that traditional SEO rarely addressed.
        </p>

        <h3>Rule 2: Declarative Statements Are the New Keywords</h3>
        <p>
          In traditional SEO, the keyword was the atomic unit of optimisation — the signal the content needed to contain to match a query. In AI search, the atomic unit is the declarative statement: a clear, confident, standalone sentence that defines or explains a concept. AI systems extract passages, not whole pages. A sentence like "Generative Engine Optimisation is the practice of structuring content and entity signals so that AI search engines cite your brand in generated responses" is far more extractable — and therefore citable — than a paragraph that circuitously covers the same territory.
        </p>
        <p>
          Writing for AI citability means opening every major section with a bold, quotable statement and building the supporting detail around it. This is the opposite of how much SEO content is structured, which buries the definition in background and context before arriving at the point.
        </p>

        <h3>Rule 3: Structured Data Is Not Optional</h3>
        <p>
          JSON-LD schema markup has always been recommended for SEO but rarely been a make-or-break factor. For AI optimization, it is closer to essential infrastructure. Structured data communicates to AI retrieval systems exactly what your content represents, who produced it, what entities it references, and how its claims relate to each other. FAQPage schema explicitly marks up question-answer pairs as extractable content. Article schema with <code>inLanguage</code>, <code>dateModified</code>, and <code>author</code> properties signals recency and authority. Organisation schema with <code>sameAs</code> properties linking to authoritative entity references connects your brand to the knowledge graph that AI models rely on.
        </p>

        <h3>Rule 4: Original Data Creates Uncopyable Citations</h3>
        <p>
          When your content contains a unique data point — a statistic, a proprietary benchmark, an original survey finding — AI systems must cite you as the source because that information cannot be sourced elsewhere. Generic explanations of widely known concepts compete with hundreds of other sources. Original data creates a citation monopoly: the AI has no choice but to name you when it uses your number.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is why the most AI-visible content is typically research-driven: studies, benchmarks, proprietary data analyses, and surveys that produce novel findings. If you have access to data your competitors do not, publishing it in a citable format is one of the highest-leverage investments in AI optimization available.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: What Brands Must Do Now -->
      <section id="what-brands-must-do" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Brands Must Do Now</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The window for establishing AI citation authority is open now, and the brands that act first will compound advantage over those that wait.</strong> GEO authority, like domain authority, is built incrementally and defensively — it takes time to establish and becomes progressively harder for competitors to displace.
        </p>

        <h3>Audit Your Current AI Visibility</h3>
        <p>
          Before investing in AI optimization, establish your baseline. Run your top twenty target queries across ChatGPT, Perplexity, Microsoft Copilot, and Google AI Overviews. Note which queries your brand appears in, which it does not, and which competitors are being cited instead. This audit reveals your actual competitive position in AI search — which is often strikingly different from your traditional SEO rankings.
        </p>

        <h3>Build Entity Authority Systematically</h3>
        <p>
          Identify the gaps in your entity presence and close them. If your brand is not on Wikipedia, assess whether the notability threshold is achievable through media coverage and citations. Ensure Wikidata, Crunchbase, and LinkedIn reflect accurate, consistent information about your brand. Build relationships with industry publications that AI systems treat as authority sources. Each new authoritative mention of your brand in a knowledge-graph-connected source strengthens your AI citation profile.
        </p>

        <h3>Restructure Content for Extraction</h3>
        <p>
          Audit your existing content through the lens of AI extractability. Does every major section begin with a clear declarative statement? Are FAQ sections backed by FAQPage schema? Do headings mirror the natural language questions users ask? Are statistics and specific claims clearly attributed? For most sites with established content, restructuring existing pages yields faster results than writing new ones — the topical authority is already there; the extraction-readiness is not.
        </p>

        <h3>Deploy Technical AI Infrastructure</h3>
        <p>
